.SH İSİM
top \N'45' display Linux tasks    

.SH KULLANIM 
.nf
\fBtop \N'45'hv \fR| \fB\N'45'bcHisS \N'45'd \fR\fIdelay \fR\fB\N'45'n \fR\fIiterations \fR\fB\N'45'p \fR\fIpid \fR[, \fIpid \fR...]

The traditional switches \N'39'\N'45'\N'39' and whitespace are optional.
.fi       

.SH DESCRIPTION     
The  \fBtop\fR  program provides a dynamic real\N'45'time view of a running system.  It can display \fBsystem\fR summary information as well as a list of  \fBtasks\fR currently  being managed  by the Linux kernel.  The types of system summary information shown and the types, order and size of information displayed for tasks are all  user  con\N'45' figurable and that configuration can be made persistent across restarts.     

The program provides a limited interactive interface for process manipulation as well as a much more extensive interface for personal configuration   \N'45'\N'45'   encom\N'45' passing  every aspect of its operation.  And while \fBtop\fR is referred to throughout this document, you are free to name the program anything  you  wish.   That  new name,  possibly  an alias, will then be reflected on top\N'39's display and used when reading and writing a configuration file.     
   

.SH OVERVIEW     

.SS Operation       
When operating top, the two most important keys are help (\N'39'h\N'39' or \N'39'?\N'39')  and  quit (\N'39'q\N'39')  key.   Alternatively,  you could simply use the traditional interrupt key (\N'39'^C\N'39') when you\N'39're done.       

When you start top for the first time, you\N'39'll be presented with the  traditional screen  elements: 1) Summary Area; 2) Message/Prompt Line; 3) Columns Header; 4) Task Area.  There will, however, be some differences when compared to the former top.       

.br
.ns
.TP 3
\fBHighlighting\fR
\fBSummary_Area\fR:  There  is  no highlighting for load/uptime and only values are highlighted for other elements.         

\fBTask_Area\fR: Tasks running (or ready to run) will be highlighted, and  bold  is only one way of emphasizing such processes.         

.TP 3
\fBContent/Labels\fR
\fBSummary_Area\fR:  The  program  name  is shown, perhaps a symlink or alias.  The Cpu(s) state label hints at other possibilities.   The  memory  stats  use  a lower case \N'39'k\N'39'.         

\fBColumns_Header\fR:  Will  show  a  new  field and some changed labels.  More new fields will be found as you customize your top.         

.PP       
.br
.ns
.TP 
\fBBilgi:\fR
The width of top\N'39's display will be limited to 512  positions.   Displaying all  fields  requires a minimum of 160 characters.  The remaining width could be used for the \N'39'Command\N'39' column.       

.PP     

