.SH COMMAND\N'45'LINE OPTIONS     
The command\N'45'line syntax for top consists of:     
 
.nf
\fBtop \N'45'hv \fR| \fB\N'45'bcHisS \N'45'd \fR\fIdelay \fR\fB\N'45'n \fR\fIiterations \fR\fB\N'45'p \fR\fIpid \fR[, \fIpid \fR...]
\ 
.fi     
The typically mandatory  switches  (\N'39'\N'45'\N'39')  and  even  whitespace  are  completely optional.     
       
.br
.ns
.TP 5
\fB\N'45'b\fR           
\fBBatch mode\fR operation
.br
Starts  top  in \N'39'Batch mode\N'39', which could be useful for sending output from top to other programs or to a file.  In this  mode,  top  will  not  accept input  and  runs  until  the iterations limit you\N'39've set with the \N'39'\N'45'n\N'39' com\N'45' mand\N'45'line option or until killed.           
         
.TP 5
\fB\N'45'c\fR           
\fBCommand line/Program name\fR toggle
.br
Starts top with the last remembered \N'39'c\N'39' state reversed.  Thus, if  top  was displaying  command lines, now that field will show program names, and visa versa.  See the \N'39'c\N'39' interactive command for additional information.           
         
.TP 5
\fB\N'45'd\fR           
\fBDelay time\fR interval as:  \fB\N'45'd ss.tt\fR (\fIseconds.tenths\fR)
.br
Specifies the delay between screen updates, and overrides the corresponding value  in  one\N'39's personal configuration file or the startup default.  Later this can be changed with the \N'39'd\N'39' or \N'39's\N'39' interactive commands.           

Fractional seconds are honored, but a negative number is not  allowed.   In all  cases,  however,  such  changes  are  prohibited  if top is running in \N'39'Secure mode\N'39', except for root (unless  the  \N'39's\N'39'  command\N'45'line  option  was used).   For  additional  information on \N'39'Secure mode\N'39' see topic 5a. SYSTEM Configuration File.           
         
.TP 5
\fB\N'45'h\fR           
\fBHelp\fR
.br
Show library version and the usage prompt, then quit.           
         
.TP 5
\fB\N'45'H\fR           
\fBThreads\fR toggle
.br
Starts top with the last remembered \N'39'H\N'39' state reversed.  When  this  toggle is On, all individual threads will be displayed.  Otherwise, top displays a summation of all threads in a process.           
         
.TP 5
\fB\N'45'i\fR           
\fBIdle Processes\fR toggle
.br
Starts top with the last remembered \N'39'i\N'39' state reversed.  When  this  toggle is Off, tasks that are idled or zombied will not be displayed.           
         
.TP 5
\fB\N'45'n\fR           
\fBNumber of iterations\fR limit as:  \fB\N'45'n \fR\fInumber\fR
.br
Specifies  the  maximum number of iterations, or frames, top should produce before ending.           
         
.TP 5
\fB\N'45'u\fR           
\fBMonitor by user\fR as:  \fB\N'45'u \fR\fIsomebody\fR
.br
Monitor only processes with an effective UID or  user  name  matching  that given.           
         
.TP 5
\fB\N'45'U\fR           
\fBMonitor by user\fR as:  \fB\N'45'U \fR\fIsomebody\fR
.br
Monitor  only  processes with a UID or user name matching that given.  This matches real, effective, saved, and filesystem UIDs.           
         
.TP 5
\fB\N'45'p\fR           
\fBMonitor PIDs\fR as:  \fB\N'45'p\fR\fIn1\fR \fB\N'45'p\fR\fIn2\fR ...  or  \fB\N'45'p\fR\fIn1\fR, \fIn2\fR [,...]
.br
Monitor only processes with specified process  IDs.   This  option  can  be given  up to 20 times, or you can provide a comma delimited list with up to 20 pids.  Co\N'45'mingling both approaches is permitted.           

This is a command\N'45'line option only.  And should you wish to return to  nor\N'45' mal  operation,  it  is not necessary to quit and and restart top  \N'45'\N'45'  just issue the \N'39'=\N'39' interactive command.           
         
.TP 5
\fB\N'45's\fR           
\fBSecure mode\fR operation
.br
Starts top with secure mode forced, even for root.  This mode is far better controlled through the system configuration file (see topic 5. FILES).           
         
.TP 5
\fB\N'45'S\fR           
\fBCumulative time mode\fR toggle
.br
Starts  top  with the last remembered \N'39'S\N'39' state reversed.  When \N'39'Cumulative mode\N'39' is On, each process is listed with the cpu time that it and its  dead children  have used.  See the \N'39'S\N'39' interactive command for additional infor\N'45' mation regarding this mode.           
         
.TP 5
\fB\N'45'v\fR           
\fBVersion\fR
.br
Show library version and the usage prompt, then quit.           
         
.PP        

.SH FIELDS / COLUMNS     

.SS DESCRIPTIONS of Fields       
Listed below are top\N'39's available fields.  They are always  associated  with  the letter  shown, regardless of the position you may have established for them with the \N'39'o\N'39' (Order fields) interactive command.       

Any field is selectable as the sort field, and  you  control  whether  they  are sorted  high\N'45'to\N'45'low  or  low\N'45'to\N'45'high.  For additional information on sort provi\N'45' sions see topic 3c. TASK Area Commands.       
         
.br
.ns
.TP 3
a: \fBPID\fR \N'45'\N'45' Process Id             
The task\N'39's unique process ID, which periodically wraps, though never restarting at zero.             
           
.TP 3
b: \fBPPID\fR \N'45'\N'45' Parent Process Pid             
The process ID of a task\N'39's parent.             
           
.TP 3
c: \fBRUSER\fR \N'45'\N'45' Real User Name             
The real user name of the task\N'39's owner.             
           
.TP 3
d: \fBUID\fR \N'45'\N'45' User Id             
The effective user ID of the task\N'39's owner.             
           
.TP 3
e: \fBUSER\fR \N'45'\N'45' User Name             
The effective user name of the task\N'39's owner.             
           
.TP 3
f: \fBGROUP\fR \N'45'\N'45' Group Name             
The effective group name of the task\N'39's owner.             
           
.TP 3
g: \fBTTY\fR \N'45'\N'45' Controlling Tty             
The  name  of  the  controlling terminal.  This is usually the device (serial port, pty, etc.) from which the process was started, and which  it  uses  for input  or output.  However, a task need not be associated with a terminal, in which case you\N'39'll see \N'39'?\N'39' displayed.             
           
.TP 3
h: \fBPR\fR \N'45'\N'45' Priority             
The priority of the task.             
           
.TP 3
i: \fBNI\fR \N'45'\N'45' Nice value             
The nice value of the task.  A negative nice  value  means  higher  priority, whereas  a positive nice value means lower priority.  Zero in this field sim\N'45' ply means priority will not be adjusted in determining a task\N'39's dispatchabil\N'45' ity.             
           
.TP 3
j: \fBP\fR \N'45'\N'45' Last used CPU (SMP)             
A  number  representing  the  last used processor.  In a true SMP environment this will likely change frequently since the kernel intentionally  uses  weak affinity.  Also, the very act of running top may break this weak affinity and cause more processes to change CPUs more often (because of the  extra  demand for cpu time).             
           
.TP 3
k: \fB%CPU\fR \N'45'\N'45' CPU usage             
The  task\N'39's  share  of  the  elapsed  CPU  time since the last screen update, expressed as a percentage of total CPU time.  In a true SMP  environment,  if \N'39'Irix  mode\N'39'  is  Off,  top will operate in \N'39'Solaris mode\N'39' where a task\N'39's cpu usage will be divided by the total number of CPUs.  You toggle \N'39'Irix/Solaris\N'39' modes with the \N'39'I\N'39' interactive command.             
           
.TP 3
l: \fBTIME\fR \N'45'\N'45' CPU Time             
Total CPU time the task has used since it started.  When \N'39'Cumulative mode\N'39' is On, each process is listed with the cpu time that it and  its  dead  children has  used.   You  toggle  \N'39'Cumulative mode\N'39' with \N'39'S\N'39', which is a command\N'45'line option and an interactive command.  See the \N'39'S\N'39' interactive command for addi\N'45' tional information regarding this mode.             
           
.TP 3
m: \fBTIME+\fR \N'45'\N'45' CPU Time, hundredths             
The  same  as \N'39'TIME\N'39', but reflecting more granularity through hundredths of a second.             
           
.TP 3
n: \fB%MEM\fR \N'45'\N'45' Memory usage (RES)             
A task\N'39's currently used share of available physical memory.             
           
.TP 3
o: \fBVIRT\fR \N'45'\N'45' Virtual Image (kb)             
The total amount of virtual memory used by the task.  It includes  all  code, data and shared libraries plus pages that have been swapped out.             

VIRT = SWAP + RES.             
           
.TP 3
p: \fBSWAP\fR \N'45'\N'45' Swapped size (kb)             
The swapped out portion of a task\N'39's total virtual memory image.             
           
.TP 3
q: \fBRES\fR \N'45'\N'45' Resident size (kb)             
The non\N'45'swapped physical memory a task has used.             

RES = CODE + DATA.             
           
.TP 3
r: \fBCODE\fR \N'45'\N'45' Code size (kb)             
The  amount  of physical memory devoted to executable code, also known as the \N'39'text resident set\N'39' size or TRS.             
           
.TP 3
s: \fBDATA\fR \N'45'\N'45' Data+Stack size (kb)             
The amount of physical memory devoted to other  than  executable  code,  also known as the \N'39'data resident set\N'39' size or DRS.             
           
.TP 3
t: \fBSHR\fR \N'45'\N'45' Shared Mem size (kb)             
The  amount  of shared memory used by a task.  It simply reflects memory that could be potentially shared with other processes.             
           
.TP 3
u: \fBnFLT\fR \N'45'\N'45' Page Fault count             
The number of major page faults that have occurred for a task.  A page  fault occurs  when  a process attempts to read from or write to a virtual page that is not currently present in its address space.  A major page  fault  is  when disk access is involved in making that page available.             
           
.TP 3
v: \fBnDRT\fR \N'45'\N'45' Dirty Pages count             
The  number  of pages that have been modified since they were last written to disk.  Dirty pages must be written to disk before the corresponding  physical memory location can be used for some other virtual page.             
           
.TP 3
w: \fBS\fR \N'45'\N'45' Process Status             
The status of the task which can be one of: 
.IP
.RS
.RS 3
.nf
\N'39'\fBD\fR\N'39' = uninterruptible sleep
\N'39'\fBR\fR\N'39' = running
\N'39'\fBS\fR\N'39' = sleeping
\N'39'\fBT\fR\N'39' = traced or stopped
\N'39'\fBZ\fR\N'39' = zombie
.fi
.RE
.RE
.IP

Tasks  shown  as running should be more properly thought of as \N'39'ready to run\N'39'   \N'45'\N'45'  their task_struct is simply represented on the  Linux  run\N'45'queue.   Even without  a true SMP machine, you may see numerous tasks in this state depend\N'45' ing on top\N'39's delay interval and nice value.             
           
.TP 3
x: \fBCommand\fR \N'45'\N'45' Command line or Program name             
Display the command line used to start a task or the name of  the  associated program.   You toggle between command line and name with \N'39'c\N'39', which is both a command\N'45'line option and an interactive command.             

When you\N'39've chosen to display command lines, processes without a command line (like  kernel  threads) will be shown with only the program name in parenthe\N'45' ses, as in this example: 
.IP
.RS
.RS 4
.nf
( mdrecoveryd )
.fi
.RE
.RE
.IP

Either form of display is subject to potential truncation if it\N'39's too long to fit  in  this  field\N'39's  current  width.  That width depends upon other fields selected, their order and the current screen width.             

.RS 3
.br
.ns
.TP 
\fBBilgi:\fR
The \N'39'Command\N'39' field/column is unique, in that it  is  not  fixed\N'45'width. When  displayed, this column will be allocated all remaining screen width (up to the maximum 512 characters) to provide for the potential growth of program names into command lines.             

.PP
.RE
.IP           

.TP 3
y: WCHAN \N'45'\N'45' Sleeping in Function             
Depending  on  the  availability  of the kernel link map (\N'39'System.map\N'39'), this field will show the name or the address of the kernel function in  which  the task  is currently sleeping.  Running tasks will display a dash (\N'39'\N'45'\N'39') in this column.             

.RS 3
.br
.ns
.TP 
\fBBilgi:\fR
By displaying this field, top\N'39's own working set will  be  increased  by over  700Kb.   Your  only means of reducing that overhead will be to stop and restart top.             

.PP
.RE
.IP           

.TP 3
z: \fBFlags\fR \N'45'\N'45' Task Flags             
This  column  represents  the  task\N'39's  current  scheduling  flags  which  are expressed in hexadecimal notation and with zeros suppressed.  These flags are officially documented in %lt;linux/sched.h>.  Less formal documentation can also be found on the \N'39'Fields select\N'39' and \N'39'Order fields\N'39' screens.             
           
.PP                 

.SS SELECTING and ORDERING Columns       
After  pressing  the  interactive  commands  \N'39'\fBf\fR\N'39'  (Fields  select) or \N'39'\fBo\fR\N'39' (Order fields) you will be shown a screen containing the current \fBfields string\fR followed by names and descriptions for all fields.       

Here  is  a sample fields string from one of top\N'39's four windows/field groups and an explanation of the conventions used:       
         
.IP \fB\N'45'\fR 3
Sample fields string: 
.IP
.RS
.RS 4
.nf
ANOPQRSTUVXbcdefgjlmyzWHIK
.fi
.RE
.RE
.IP
         
.IP \fB\N'45'\fR 3
The order of displayed fields corresponds to the order of the letters in that string.         
         
.IP \fB\N'45'\fR 3
If the letter is \fIupper case\fR the corresponding field itself will then be shown as part of the task display (screen width permitting).   This  will  also  be indicated by a leading asterisk (\N'39'*\N'39'), as in this excerpt: 
.IP
.RS
.RS 4
.nf
...
\fB* K: %CPU\fR       = CPU usage
\  l: TIME       = CPU Time
\  m: TIME+      = CPU Time, hundredths
\fB* N: %MEM\fR       = Memory usage (RES)
\fB* O: VIRT\fR       = Virtual Image (kb)
...
.fi
.RE
.RE
.IP         

.PP              
.br
.ns
.TP 3
\fBFields select\fR screen \N'45'\N'45' the \N'39'\fBf\fR\N'39' interactive command           
You  \fItoggle\fR  the \fBdisplay\fR of a field by simply pressing the corresponding letter.           
         
.TP 3
\fBOrder fields\fR screen \N'45'\N'45' the \N'39'\fBo\fR\N'39' interactive command           
You \fImove\fR a field to the \fBleft\fR by pressing the corresponding \fBupper case\fR  letter and to the \fBright\fR with the \fBlower case\fR letter.           
         
.PP     

.SS CPU States       
The CPU states are shown in the Summary Area. They are always shown  as  a  percentage and are for the time between now and the last refresh.       

.br
.ns
.TP 3
\fB us\fR \N'45'\N'45' User CPU time
The time the CPU has spent running users\N'39' processes that are not niced.         

.TP 3
\fB sy\fR \N'45'\N'45' System CPU time
The time the CPU has spent running the kernel and its processes.         

.TP 3
\fB ni\fR \N'45'\N'45' Nice CPU time
The time the CPU has spent running users\N'39' proccess that have been niced.         

.TP 3
\fB wa\fR \N'45'\N'45' iowait
Amount of time the CPU has been waiting for I/O to complete.         

.TP 3
\fB hi\fR \N'45'\N'45' Hardware IRQ
The amount of time the CPU has been servicing hardware interrupts.         

.TP 3
\fB si\fR \N'45'\N'45' Software Interrupts
The amount of time the CPU has been servicing software interrupts.         

.PP        

.SH INTERACTIVE COMMANDS     
Listed  below  is  a  brief  index of commands within categories.  Some commands appear more than once  \N'45'\N'45'  their meaning or scope may vary depending on the con\N'45' text in which they are issued.     

.br
.ns
.TP 
\ \ GLOBAL Commands
<Ret/Sp> ?, =, A, B, d, G, h, I, k, q, r, s, W, Z       

.TP 
\ \ SUMMARY Area Commands
l, m, t, 1       

.TP 
\ \ TASK Area Commands 
.nf
Appearance:  b, x, y, z
Content:     c, f, H, o, S, u
Size:        #, i, n
Sorting:     <, >, F, O, R
.fi
.TP 
\ \ COLOR Mapping
<Ret>, a, B, b, H, M, q, S, T, w, z, 0 \N'45' 7       

