\N'45', _, =, +, A, a, G, g, w       

.PP     

.SS GLOBAL Commands       
The  global  interactive  commands are \fBalways\fR available in both full\N'45'screen mode and alternate\N'45'display mode.  However, some of these interactive commands are \fBnot available\fR when running in \N'39'Secure mode\N'39'.       

If  you wish to know in advance whether or not your top has been secured, simply ask for help and view the system summary on the second line.       
         
.br
.ns
.TP 7
\ \ <\fBEnter\fR> or <\fBSpace\fR>: \fBRefresh Display\fR
These commands do nothing, they are simply ignored.  However,  they  will awaken  top and following receipt of any input the entire display will be repainted.           

Use either of these keys if you have a large delay interval and  wish  to see current status,           

.TP 7
\N'39'\fB?\fR\N'39' or \N'39'\fBh\fR\N'39': \fIHelp\fR
There  are  two help levels available.  The first will provide a reminder of all the basic interactive commands.  If top is  \fIsecured\fR,  that  screen will be abbreviated.           

Typing  \N'39'h\N'39'  or  \N'39'?\N'39'  on that help screen will take you to help for those interactive commands applicable to alternate\N'45'display mode.           

.TP 7
\ \ \N'39'=\N'39': \fIExit_Task_Limits\fR
Removes restrictions on which tasks are shown.  This command will reverse any  \N'39'i\N'39'  (idle tasks) and \N'39'n\N'39' (max tasks) commands that might be active. It also provides for an \N'39'exit\N'39' from PID monitoring.  See  the  \N'39'\N'45'p\N'39'  com\N'45' mand\N'45'line option for a discussion of PID monitoring.           

When  operating  in  alternate\N'45'display  mode  this command has a slightly broader meaning.           

.TP 7
\ \ \N'39'\fBA\fR\N'39': \fIAlternate Display Mode toggle\fR
This command will switch between full\N'45'screen mode  and  alternate\N'45'display mode.   See  topic 4. ALTERNATE\N'45'DISPLAY Mode and the \N'39'G\N'39' interactive com\N'45' mand for insight into \N'39'current\N'39' windows and field groups.           

.TP 7
\ \ \N'39'\fBB\fR\N'39': \fIBold Disable/Enable toggle\fR
This command will influence use of the  \N'39'bold\N'39'  terminfo  capability  and alters  \fIboth\fR  the  summary  area  and task area for the \N'39'current\N'39' window. While it is intended primarily for use with dumb  terminals,  it  can  be applied anytime.           

.RS 7
.br
.ns
.TP 
\fBBilgi:\fR
When this toggle is On and top is operating in monochrome mode, the \fBentire display\fR will appear as normal text.  Thus, unless the  \N'39'x\N'39'  and/or \N'39'y\N'39'  toggles are using reverse for emphasis, there will be no visual con\N'45' firmation that they are even on.           

.PP
.RE
.IP

.TP 7
* \N'39'\fBd\fR\N'39' or \N'39'\fBs\fR\N'39'
\fIChange Delay Time interval\fR
.br
You will be prompted to enter the delay time, in seconds, between display updates.           

Fractional  seconds  are  honored,  but a negative number is not allowed. Entering 0 causes (nearly) continuous  updates,  with  an  unsatisfactory display  as  the system and tty driver try to keep up with top\N'39's demands. The delay value is inversely proportional to system loading,  so  set  it with care.           

If  at  any  time you wish to know the current delay time, simply ask for help and view the system summary on the second line.           

.TP 7
\ \ \N'39'\fBG\fR\N'39'
\fIChoose Another Window/Field Group \fR
.br
You will be prompted to enter a number between 1 and  4  designating  the window/field  group  which should be made the \N'39'current\N'39' window.  You will soon grow comfortable with these 4 windows, especially after  experiment\N'45' ing with alternate\N'45'display mode.           

.TP 7
\ \ \N'39'\fBI\fR\N'39'
\fIIrix/Solaris Mode toggle\fR
.br
When  operating  in  \N'39'Solaris mode\N'39' (\N'39'I\N'39' toggled \fIOff\fR), a task\N'39's cpu usage will be divided by the total number of CPUs.  After issuing this command, you\N'39'll be informed of the new state of this toggle.           

.TP 7
\ \ \N'39'\fBu\fR\N'39'
\fIselect a user\fR
.br
You  will  be prompted for a UID or username. Only processes belonging to the selected user will be displayed. This option matches on the effective UID.           

.TP 7
\ \ \N'39'\fBU\fR\N'39'
\fIselect a user\fR
.br
You  will  be prompted for a UID or username. Only processes belonging to the selected user will be displayed. This option  matches  on  the  real, effective, saved, and filesystem UID.           

.TP 7
* \N'39'\fBk\fR\N'39'
\fI Kill a task\fR
.br
You  will be prompted for a PID and then the signal to send.  The default signal, as reflected in the prompt, is SIGTERM.  However,  you  can  send any signal, via number or name.           

If  you wish to abort the kill process, do one of the following depending on your progress: 
.IP
.RS
.RS 3
.nf
1) at the pid prompt, just press <Enter>
2) at the signal prompt, type 0
.fi
.RE
.RE
.IP           

.TP 7
\ \ \N'39'\fBq\fR\N'39'
\fIQuit\fR

.TP 7
* \N'39'\fBr\fR\N'39'
\fIRenice a Task\fR
.br
You will be prompted for a PID and then the value to nice it to.   Enter\N'45' ing  a positive value will cause a process to lose priority.  Conversely, a negative value will cause a process to be viewed more favorably by  the kernel.           

.TP 7
\ \ \N'39'\fBW\fR\N'39'
\fIWrite the Configuration File\fR
.br
This  will  save all of your options and toggles plus the current display mode and delay time.  By issuing this command just before  quitting  top, you will be able restart later in exactly that same state.           

.TP 7
\ \ \N'39'\fBZ\fR\N'39'
\fIChange Color Mapping\fR
.br
This key will take you to a separate screen where you can change the col\N'45' ors for the \N'39'current\N'39' window, or for all windows.  For details  regarding this interactive command see topic 3d. COLOR Mapping.           

.PP       
The commands shown with an asterisk (\N'39'*\N'39') are not available in \N'39'Secure mode\N'39',   nor will they be shown on the level\N'45'1 help screen.       
     

.SS SUMMARY Area Commands       
The summary area interactive commands are \fBalways available\fR in  both  full\N'45'screen mode  and  alternate\N'45'display mode.  They affect the beginning lines of your dis\N'45' play and will determine the position of messages and prompts.       

These commands always impact just the \N'39'current\N'39' window/field group.   See  topic 4. ALTERNATE\N'45'DISPLAY Mode and the \N'39'G\N'39' interactive command for insight into \N'39'cur\N'45' rent\N'39' windows and field groups.       

.br
.ns
.TP 7
\ \ \N'39'\fBl\fR\N'39'
\fIToggle_Load_Average/Uptime\fR  \N'45'\N'45'  On/Off
.br
This is also the line containing the program  name  (possibly  an  alias) when  operating  in  full\N'45'screen  mode  or the \N'39'current\N'39' window name when operating in alternate\N'45'display mode.         

.TP 7
\ \ \N'39'\fBm\fR\N'39'
\fIToggle_Memory/Swap_Usage\fR  \N'45'\N'45'  On/Off This command affects two summary area lines.         

.TP 7
\ \ \N'39'\fBt\fR\N'39'
\fIToggle_Task/Cpu_States\fR  \N'45'\N'45'  On/Off
.br
This command affects from 2 to many summary area lines, depending on  the state of the \N'39'1\N'39' toggle and whether or not top is running under true SMP.         

.TP 7
\ \ \N'39'\fB1\fR\N'39'
\fIToggle_Single/Separate_Cpu_States\fR  \N'45'\N'45'  On/Off
.br
This command affects how the \N'39't\N'39' command\N'39's Cpu States portion  is  shown. Although  this  toggle  exists  primarily to serve massively\N'45'parallel SMP machines, it is not restricted to solely SMP environments.         

When you see \N'39'Cpu(s):\N'39' in the summary area, the \N'39'1\N'39' toggle is On and  all cpu  information  is  gathered  in a single line.  Otherwise, each cpu is displayed separately as: \N'39'Cpu0, Cpu1, ...\N'39'         

.PP       
.br
.ns
.TP 7
\fBBilgi:\fR
If the entire summary area has been toggled Off for any window, you  would be left with just the \fBmessage line\fR.  In that way, you will have maximized avail\N'45' able task rows but (temporarily) sacrificed the program name in full\N'45'screen mode or the \N'39'current\N'39' window name when in alternate\N'45'display mode.       

.PP
     

.SS TASK Area Commands       
The task area interactive commands are \fBalways\fR available in full\N'45'screen mode.       

The task area interactive commands are never available in alternate\N'45'display mode if the \N'39'current\N'39' window\N'39's task display has been toggled Off (see topic 4. ALTER\N'45' NATE\N'45'DISPLAY Mode).       

.br
.ns
.TP 2
\fBAPPEARANCE\fR of task window
The  following commands will also be influenced by the state of the global \N'39'B\N'39' (bold disable) toggle.         


.RS 2
.br
.ns
.TP 5
\N'39'\fBb\fR\N'39'
\fIBold/Reverse toggle\fR
.br
This command will impact how the \N'39'x\N'39' and \N'39'y\N'39' toggles are displayed.  Fur\N'45' ther, it will only be available when at least one of those toggles is On.             

.TP 5
\N'39'\fBx\fR\N'39'
\fIColumn Highlight toggle\fR
.br
Changes highlighting for the current sort field.  You probably don\N'39't need a  constant  visual  reminder  of  the  sort field and top hopes that you always run with \N'39'column highlight\N'39' Off, due to the cost in path\N'45'length.             

If you forget which field is being sorted this command  can  serve  as  a quick visual reminder.             

.TP 5
\N'39'\fBy\fR\N'39'
\fIRow Highlight toggle\fR
.br
Changes  highlighting  for  "running" tasks.  For additional insight into this task state, see topic 2a. DESCRIPTIONS of Fields, Process Status.             

Use of this provision  provides  important  insight  into  your  system\N'39's health.  The only costs will be a few additional tty escape sequences.             

.TP 5
\N'39'\fBz\fR\N'39'
\fIColor/Monochrome toggle\fR
.br
Switches the \N'39'current\N'39' window between your last used color scheme and the older form of black\N'45'on\N'45'white or white\N'45'on\N'45'black.  This command will  alter both  the summary area and task area but does not affect the state of the \N'39'x\N'39', \N'39'y\N'39' or \N'39'b\N'39' toggles.           

.PP
.RE
.IP       

.TP 2
\fBCONTENT\fR of task window

.RS 2
.br
.ns
.TP 5
\N'39'\fBc\fR\N'39'
\fICommand Line/Program Name toggle\fR
.br
This command will be honored whether or not the \N'39'Command\N'39' column is  cur\N'45' rently  visible.  Later, should that field come into view, the change you applied will be seen.           

.TP 5
\N'39'\fBf\fR\N'39' and \N'39'\fBo\fR\N'39'
\fIFields select or Order fields\fR
.br
These keys display separate screens where you can change which fields are displayed  and their order.  For additional information on these interac\N'45' tive commands see topic 2b. SELECTING and ORDERING Columns.           

.TP 5
\N'39'\fBH\fR\N'39'
\fIThreads toggle\fR When this toggle is On, all individual threads will be displayed.  Other\N'45' wise, top displays a summation of all threads in a process.           

.TP 5
\N'39'\fBS\fR\N'39'
\fICumulative Time Mode toggle\fR
.br
When  \N'39'Cumulative  mode\N'39'  is On, each process is listed with the cpu time that it and its dead children have used.           

When Off, programs that fork into many separate tasks  will  appear  less demanding.   For  programs like \N'39'init\N'39' or a shell this is appropriate but for others, like compilers, perhaps not.  Experiment with two  task  win\N'45' dows  sharing  the  same sort field but with different \N'39'S\N'39' states and see which representation you prefer.           

After issuing this command, you\N'39'll be informed of the new state  of  this toggle.   If you wish to know in advance whether or not \N'39'Cumulative mode\N'39' is in effect, simply ask for help and view the window summary on the sec\N'45' ond line.           

.TP 5
\N'39'\fBu\fR\N'39'
\fIShow_Specific_User_Only\fR
.br
You  will  be  prompted to enter the name of the user to display.  There\N'45' after, in that task window only matching User ID\N'39's will be shown, or pos\N'45' sibly no tasks will be shown.           

Later,  if you wish to monitor all tasks again, re\N'45'issue this command but just press <Enter> at the prompt, without providing a name.           

.PP
.RE
.IP       

.TP 2
\fBSIZE\fR of task window

.RS 2
.br
.ns
.TP 5
\N'39'\fBi\fR\N'39'
\fIIdle Processes toggle\fR
.br
Displays all tasks or just active tasks.  When this toggle is Off,  idled or zombied processes will not be displayed.           

If  this  command  is  applied  to  the  last task display when in alter\N'45' nate\N'45'display mode, then it will not affect  the  window\N'39's  size,  as  all prior task displays will have already been painted.           

.TP 5
\N'39'\fBn\fR\N'39' or \N'39'\fB#\fR\N'39'
\fISet Maximum Tasks\fR
.br
You will be prompted to enter the number of tasks to display.  The lessor of your number and available screen rows will be used.           

When used in alternate\N'45'display mode, this is the command that  gives  you precise  control  over  the  size of each currently visible task display, except for the very last.  It will not affect the last window\N'39's size,  as all prior task displays will have already been painted.           

.RS 5
.br
.ns
.TP 
\fBBilgi:\fR
If  you wish to increase the size of the last visible task display when in alternate\N'45'display mode, simply decrease the size of the task dis\N'45' play(s) above it.           

.PP
.RE
.IP

.PP
.RE
.IP       

.TP 2
\fBSORTING\fR of task window
For  compatibility, this top supports most of the former top sort keys.  Since this is primarily a service to former top users, these commands do not  appear on any help screen. 
.IP
.RS
.RS 3
.nf
\fBcommand   sorted field                  supported\fR
\  A         start time (non\N'45'display)      No
\  M         %MEM                          Yes
\  N         PID                           Yes
\  P         %CPU                          Yes
\  T         TIME+                         Yes
.fi
.RE
.RE
.IP

Before  using any of the following sort provisions, top suggests that you tem\N'45' porarily turn on column highlighting using the \N'39'x\N'39' interactive command.   That will help ensure that the actual sort environment matches your intent.       

The  following interactive commands will only be honored when the current sort field is visible.  The sort field might not be visible because: 
.IP
.RS
.RS 5
.nf
1) there is insufficient Screen Width
2) the \N'39'f\N'39' interactive command turned it Off
.fi
.RE
.RE
.IP       


.RS 2
.br
.ns
.TP 5
\N'39'\fB<\fR\N'39'
\fIMove Sort Field Left\fR
.br
Moves the sort column to the left unless the current sort  field  is  the first field being displayed.           

.TP 5
\N'39'\fB>\fR\N'39'
\fIMove Sort Field Right\fR
.br
Moves  the  sort column to the right unless the current sort field is the last field being displayed.           

.PP
.RE
.IP       

The following interactive commands will always be honored whether or  not  the current sort field is visible.       


.RS 2
.br
.ns
.TP 5
\N'39'\fBF\fR\N'39' or \N'39'\fBO\fR\N'39'
\fISelect Sort Field\fR
.br
These  keys display a separate screen where you can change which field is used as the sort column.           

If a field is selected which was not previously being displayed, it  will be forced On when you return to the top display.  However, depending upon your screen width and the order of your fields, this sort field  may  not be displayable.           

This  interactive  command  can  be a convenient way to simply verify the current sort field, when running top with column highlighting turned Off.           

.TP 5
\N'39'\fBR\fR\N'39'
\fIReverse/Normal Sort Field toggle\fR
.br
Using  this interactive command you can alternate between high\N'45'to\N'45'low and low\N'45'to\N'45'high sorts.           

.PP
.RE
.IP       

.RS 2
.br
.ns
.TP 
\fBBilgi:\fR
Field sorting uses internal values, not those in column display.   Thus, the TTY and WCHAN fields will violate strict ASCII collating sequence.       

.PP
.RE
.IP

.PP   

.SS COLOR Mapping     
When  you  issue the \N'39'Z\N'39' interactive command, you will be presented with a sepa\N'45' rate screen.  That screen can be used to change the colors in just the \N'39'current\N'39' window or in all four windows before returning to the top display.       

.br
.ns
.TP 4
\fBAvailable interactive commands\fR 
.nf
4 upper case letters to select a target
8 numbers to select a color
\fBnormal toggles available\fR
\    \N'39'B\N'39'       :bold disable/enable
\    \N'39'b\N'39'       :running tasks "bold"/reverse
\    \N'39'z\N'39'       :color/mono
\fBother commands available\fR
\    \N'39'a\N'39'/\N'39'w\N'39'   :apply, then go to next/prior
\    <Enter>   :apply and exit
\    \N'39'q\N'39'       :abandon current changes and exit

.fi
.PP
If  your  use \N'39'a\N'39' or \N'39'w\N'39' to cycle the targeted window, you will have applied the color scheme that was displayed when you left that window.  You can, of  course, easily return to any window and reapply different colors or turn colors Off com\N'45' pletely with the \N'39'z\N'39' toggle.       

The Color Mapping screen can also be used to change the  \N'39'current\N'39'  window/field group  in  either full\N'45'screen mode or alternate\N'45'display mode.  Whatever was tar\N'45' geted when \N'39'q\N'39' or <Enter> was pressed will be made current as you return to  the top display.       
        

.SH ALTERNATE\N'45'DISPLAY MODE     

.SS WINDOWS Overview       

.B Field Groups/Windows:
.RS 4         
In  full\N'45'screen  mode  there is a single window represented by the entire screen.  That single window can still be changed to display 1 of  4  dif\N'45' ferent  field  groups  (see the \N'39'G\N'39' interactive command, repeated below). Each of the 4 field groups has a unique separately  configurable  summary area and its own configurable task area.         

In  alternate\N'45'display  mode,  those  4 underlying field groups can now be made visible simultaneously, or can be turned Off  individually  at  your command.         

The  summary  area will always exist, even if it\N'39's only the message line. At any given time only one  summary  area  can  be  displayed.   However, depending  on  your  commands,  there could be from zero to four separate task displays currently showing on the screen.         
       
.RE

.B Current Window:
.RS 4         
The \N'39'current\N'39' window is the window associated with the summary  area  and the  window to which task related commands are always directed.  Since in alternate\N'45'display mode you can toggle the task display Off, some commands might be restricted for the \N'39'current\N'39' window.         

A  further  complication  arises  when you have toggled the first summary area line Off.  With the loss of the window name (the \N'39'l\N'39' toggled  line), you\N'39'll not easily know what window is the \N'39'current\N'39' window.         
       
.RE     

.SS COMMANDS for Windows       
.br
.ns
.TP 6
\ \ \N'39'\fB\N'45'\fR\N'39' or \N'39'\fB_\fR\N'39': \fIShow/Hide Window(s) toggles\fR
The  \N'39'\N'45'\N'39'  key turns the \N'39'current\N'39' window\N'39's task display On and Off.  When On, that task area will show a  minimum  of  the  columns  header  you\N'39've established  with  the  \N'39'f\N'39'  and  \N'39'o\N'39' commands.  It will also reflect any other task area options/toggles you\N'39've  applied  yielding  zero  or  more tasks.         

The  \N'39'_\N'39'  key  does  the  same for all task displays.  In other words, it switches between the currently visible task display(s) and any task  dis\N'45' play(s)  you had toggled Off.  If all 4 task displays are currently visi\N'45' ble, this interactive command will leave the summary  area  as  the  only display element.         

.TP 6
* \N'39'\fB=\fR\N'39' and \N'39'\fB+\fR\N'39': \fIEqualize (re\N'45'balance) Window(s)\fR
The \N'39'=\N'39' key forces the \N'39'current\N'39' window\N'39's task display to be visible.  It also reverses any \N'39'i\N'39' (idle tasks) and  \N'39'n\N'39'  (max  tasks)  commands  that might be active.         

The  \N'39'+\N'39'  key does the same for all windows.  The four task displays will reappear, evenly balanced.  They will also have retained  any  customiza\N'45' tions you had previously applied, except for the \N'39'i\N'39' (idle tasks) and \N'39'n\N'39' (max tasks) commands.         

.TP 6
* \N'39'\fBA\fR\N'39': \fIAlternate Display Mode toggle\fR
This command will switch between full\N'45'screen mode  and  alternate\N'45'display mode.         

The  first  time  you  issue this command, all four task displays will be shown.  Thereafter when you switch modes, you will see only the task dis\N'45' play(s) you\N'39've chosen to make visible.         

.TP 6
* \N'39'\fBa\fR\N'39' and \N'39'\fBw\fR\N'39': \fINext Window Forward/Backward\fR
This  will  change the \N'39'current\N'39' window, which in turn changes the window to which commands are directed.  These keys act in a circular fashion  so you can reach any desired \N'39'current\N'39' window using either key.         

Assuming the window name is visible (you have not toggled \N'39'l\N'39' Off), when\N'45' ever the  \N'39'current\N'39'  window  name  loses  its  emphasis/color,  that\N'39's  a reminder the task display is Off and many commands will be restricted.         

.TP 6
* \N'39'\fBG\fR\N'39': \fIChoose Another Window/Field Group\fR
You  will  be  prompted to enter a number between 1 and 4 designating the window/field group which should be made the \N'39'current\N'39' window.         

In full\N'45'screen mode, this command is necessary  to  alter  the  \N'39'current\N'39' window.  In alternate\N'45'display mode, it is simply a less convenient alter\N'45' native to the \N'39'a\N'39' and \N'39'w\N'39' commands.         

.TP 6
\ \ \N'39'\fBg\fR\N'39': \fIChange Window/Field Group Name\fR
You will be prompted for a new name to be applied to the  \N'39'current\N'39'  win\N'45'       dow.  It does not require that the window name be visible (the \N'39'l\N'39' toggle       to be On).         

.PP       
The interactive commands shown with an asterisk (\N'39'*\N'39') have use beyond  alternate\N'45'display mode.       
.RS 6
.nf
\N'39'=\N'39', \N'39'A\N'39', \N'39'G\N'39'  are always available
\N'39'a\N'39', \N'39'w\N'39'       act the same when color mapping
.fi
.RE
        

.SH FILES     

.SS SYSTEM Configuration File       
The  presence  of this file will influence which version of the \N'39'help\N'39' screen is shown to an ordinary user.  More importantly, it will limit what ordinary  users are  allowed to do when top is running.  They will not be able to issue the fol\N'45' lowing commands.       
.RS 3
.nf
k         Kill a task
r         Renice a task
d or s    Change delay/sleep interval
.fi
.RE

The system configuration file is not created by top.  Rather,  you  create  this file  manually and place it in the /etc directory.  Its name must be \N'39'toprc\N'39' and must have no leading \N'39'.\N'39' (period).  It must have only two lines.       

Here is an example of the contents of /etc/toprc:       
.RS 3
.nf
s         # line 1: \N'39'secure\N'39' mode switch
5.0       # line 2: \N'39'delay\N'39'  interval in seconds
.fi
.RE
     

.SS PERSONAL Configuration File       
This file is written as \N'39'$HOME/.your\N'45'name\N'45'4\N'45'top\N'39' + \N'39'rc\N'39'.  Use the  \N'39'W\N'39'  interac\N'45' tive command to create it or update it.       

Here is the general layout:       
.RS 3
.nf
global    # line 1: the program name/alias notation
\  "       # line 2: id,altscr,irixps,delay,curwin
per ea    # line a: winname,fieldscur
window    # line b: winflags,sortindx,maxtasks
\  "       # line c: summclr,msgsclr,headclr,taskclr
.fi
.RE

If the $HOME variable is not present, top will try to write the personal config\N'45' uration file to the current directory, subject to permissions.       
        

.SH STUPID TRICKS SAMPLER     
Many of these \N'39'tricks\N'39' work best when you give top a scheduling boost.  So  plan on starting him with a nice value of \N'45'10, assuming you\N'39've got the authority.     


.SS Kernel Magic       
For these stupid tricks, top needs full\N'45'screen mode.       
         
.IP \fB\N'45'\fR 3
The  user  interface,  through prompts and help, intentionally implies that the delay interval is limited to tenths of a second.  However, you\N'39're  free to set any desired delay.  If you want to see Linux at his scheduling best, try a delay of .09 seconds or less.         

For this experiment, under x\N'45'windows open an xterm and maximize  it.   Then do the following:         

.RS  
.IP \fB·\fR 3
provide a scheduling boost and tiny delay via: 
.RS 4
.nf
nice \N'45'n \N'45'10 top \N'45'd.09
.fi
.RE 
.IP \fB·\fR 3
keep sorted column highlighting Off to minimize path length 
.IP \fB·\fR 3
turn On reverse row highlighting for emphasis 
.IP \fB·\fR 3
try various sort columns (TIME/MEM work well), and normal or reverse sorts to bring the most active processes into view
.PP         
.RE
.IP

What  you\N'39'll  see is a very busy Linux doing what he\N'39's always done for you, but there was no program available to illustrate this.         

.IP \fB\N'45'\fR 3
Under an xterm using \N'39'white\N'45'on\N'45'black\N'39' colors, try setting top\N'39's task  color to  black  and  be sure that task highlighting is set to bold, not reverse. Then set the delay interval to around .3 seconds.         

After bringing the most active processes into view, what you\N'39'll see are the ghostly images of just the currently running tasks.         

.IP \fB\N'45'\fR 3
Delete  the  existing rcfile, or create a new symlink.  Start this new ver\N'45' sion then type \N'39'T\N'39' (a secret key, see topic 3c. TASK Area  Commands,  Sort\N'45' ing)  followed by \N'39'W\N'39' and \N'39'q\N'39'.  Finally, restart the program with \N'45'd0 (zero delay).         

Your display will be refreshed at three times the rate of the former top, a 300%  speed advantage.  As top climbs the TIME ladder, be as patient as you can while speculating on whether or not top will ever reach the top.       

.PP     

.SS Bouncing Windows       
For these stupid tricks, top needs alternate\N'45'display mode.       
         
.IP \fB\N'45'\fR 3
With 3 or 4 task displays visible, pick any window other than the last  and turn  idle  processes  Off.   Depending on where you applied \N'39'i\N'39', sometimes several task displays are bouncing and sometimes it\N'39's like an accordion, as top tries his best to allocate space.         

.IP \fB\N'45'\fR 3
Set  each  window\N'39's  summary lines differently: one with no memory; another with no states; maybe one with nothing at all, just the message line.  Then hold down \N'39'a\N'39' or \N'39'w\N'39' and watch a variation on bouncing windows  \N'45'\N'45'  hopping windows.         

.IP \fB\N'45'\fR 3
Display all 4 windows and for each, in turn, set  idle  processes  to  Off. You\N'39've just entered the "extreme bounce" zone.         

.PP            

.SS The Big Bird Window       
This stupid trick also requires alternate\N'45'display mode.       
         
.IP \fB\N'45'\fR 3
Display  all  4  windows  and make sure that 1:Def is the \N'39'current\N'39' window. Then, keep increasing window size until the all the other task displays are "pushed out of the nest".         

When  they\N'39've all been displaced, toggle between all visible/invisible win\N'45' dows.  Then ponder this:         

.IP
is top fibbing or telling honestly your imposed truth?         

.PP       
